How to use this as the shell to combine everything (clean, defensible method)

Step 1: Freeze this as the “Baseline Framework”
Lock the dimensions, units, and hour allocations as the spine. That prevents “random curriculum drift” and keeps the rebuild auditable.

Step 2: Build a crosswalk from “current reality” into this spine
For every current handout/slide/deck/activity you’re using now, map it into:

Dimension → Unit → Competency (where possible)
If something doesn’t fit, it’s either:

A replacement (same slot, newer content), or

An add-on (requires hour tradeoff or becomes “outside-hours / enrichment”)

Step 3: Produce a combined master with a change log
Your CEO problem is a change-log problem. The fix is boring but bulletproof:

“Baseline (2022)”

“Approved modifications (date / approver / what changed / why)”
Even if leadership “forgets,” the document won’t.

Step 4: Split student-facing vs staff-facing (optional but smart)
This workbook mixes policy, curriculum outline, and training content. You can keep the shell, but separating:

Student Handbook section (rules/rights/discipline)

Curriculum workbook section (units/materials)
…makes updates cleaner and stops policy edits from accidentally messing with instructional content.

When you’re ready to move on, the next action is simple: we pull the Dimension/Unit skeleton out of this workbook exactly as written, then start dropping your current content into the matching slots and flagging anything that forces an hour/structure decision.


