You said:
recommendation to keep track of all this work. should i use notion or something similar. tell me what would be the best place to create a new curriculum. me personally i use google classroom to keep all my stuff. they use share point which is horrible because people make copies and change the master shit all the time. this is what got us in this shit hole the first place. but i need a spot to build out and then i can move it to where ever. i dont even mind if we code it out somewhere. 
ChatGPT said:

Thought for 1m 8s
You don’t have a “tool” problem. You have a “master-copy governance” problem. The best place to build the new curriculum is wherever you can enforce: one source of truth, version history, and controlled changes.

My recommendation: Git-based “docs-as-code” as the master, then publish anywhere you want
Use a private GitHub repo (or Azure DevOps if your org lives in Microsoft land) as the canonical source. Write the curriculum in Markdown (or keep Word/PDF files too), and publish it as a simple documentation site (MkDocs/Docusaurus) or export PDFs for staff.

Why this wins:

Every change is tracked, attributable, and revertible (no mystery edits).

You can require reviews/approvals before anything becomes “master.”

You can tag official versions (“2022 baseline,” “2026 combined v1”), and keep multiple versions cleanly (tools like “mike” exist specifically to manage versioned MkDocs docs in Git). 

SharePoint becomes a view-only “distribution mirror,” not the place people edit.

If you’re willing to “code it out somewhere,” this is the cleanest long-term fix.

Best non-code option (since you already live in Google): Google Drive/Docs as the master, with strict rules
Google Docs/Sheets/Slides have built-in version history and you can restore earlier versions (with edit permission). 

For Word/PDF files stored in Drive, Drive also keeps file versions, but older versions can be deleted after 30 days or after 100 newer versions unless you explicitly “Keep forever.” 

So Google can work if you enforce:

One Shared Drive called “Curriculum Master” with very limited editors

Everyone else is view/comment only

Required workflow: update the existing file (or upload a new version), do not make copies

“Keep forever” on milestone versions (quarterly/annually, or every approved release). 

Where Notion fits (and where it doesn’t)
Notion is great for drafting and brainstorming, but as the canonical master it’s weaker unless you’re on the right plan. Notion’s page version history is limited by plan (Free 7 days, Plus 30, Business 90; Enterprise is longer/unlimited). 

That’s not what you want for a “golden ticket” curriculum that needs receipts.

SharePoint isn’t doomed, it’s just being used wrong
SharePoint can be configured to prevent the “everyone edits the master” chaos: it supports versioning and can require check-out/check-in, which locks a file for exclusive editing until it’s checked back in. 

If your org insists on SharePoint, the fix is: master library with versioning + required checkout + restricted editors. 

But if the culture is “copy and mutate,” SharePoint will still get abused unless permissions are tight.

A practical setup that matches your reality

Build the master in Git (best) or Google Drive (second best).

Use Google Classroom purely as the student delivery layer (handouts, links, assignments).

Use SharePoint only as a read-only publishing mirror for internal staff who refuse to click anything that isn’t Microsoft.

Rules that prevent a repeat of this mess

One canonical master location. Everything else is a published copy.

No editing in the publishing location (SharePoint/Classroom).

Every approved change gets logged (date, what changed, who approved).

“Copies” are prohibited unless labeled explicitly as drafts.

If you pick one path: go Git as master, Classroom for students, SharePoint as view-only mirror. That combination is basically a padlock, a ledger, and a loudspeaker.

