ChatGPT said:

Thought for 50s
Yep. “Code it out” + “people can download PDFs” is a solved problem if you treat the curriculum like documentation.

The cleanest setup

Canonical source: a Git repo

Curriculum lives as Markdown files (plus any source docs you want to keep).

You lock the main branch so nobody can “edit the master” without a reviewed change.

Publish: a documentation site (MkDocs)

MkDocs is built for this exact use case and can deploy to GitHub Pages. 

PDFs: auto-generate + host for download
You have two good patterns:

A) PDFs available directly on the site (best day-to-day)

Use an MkDocs PDF export plugin that generates:

One combined “full curriculum” PDF

Optionally per-page PDFs

Example: mkdocs-exporter supports exporting pages and aggregating the whole site into one PDF. 

Alternative options exist too (WeasyPrint-based single-PDF plugins), but exporter is straightforward for “download button + full PDF.” 

Result: staff go to the site and click “Download PDF.” No hunting.

B) Official “releases” for PDFs (best for version control and audits)

When you tag a version (example: v2026.1), GitHub Releases can host PDF files as downloadable release assets. 

You can automate uploading the PDFs to the Release with softprops/action-gh-release. 

Result: “Here’s the approved curriculum PDF for Q2 2026” with a permanent download link, and you can always roll back.

What I’d do in your world (SharePoint culture, Google Classroom delivery)

Git repo = master

MkDocs site = staff view/download hub (HTML + PDFs)

GitHub Release PDF = the “official signed version” per quarter or per major update

Google Classroom = student delivery (link out to the site or attach the specific PDF)

SharePoint = optional mirror for distribution only, not editing

If you want a concrete blueprint (minimal moving parts)

MkDocs deploy to GitHub Pages (MkDocs supports this workflow). 

Generate PDFs during the build (plugin). 

Upload the “full curriculum PDF” as a release asset on tags. 

If you tell me where you want it hosted (GitHub Pages vs internal only), I’ll give you the exact repo structure and the build workflow file to make the site + PDFs publish automatically.

You said:
i have unlimited creation in Github pages. I also have unlimited in notion. so either way. Notion kind of kinks out if the file is too big. 
ChatGPT said:

Thought for 47s
Go GitHub Pages as the “master,” and treat PDFs as a first-class output.

Notion is great for drafting, but it’s a shaky single source of truth when the content gets big and you care about “what changed, when, and who approved it.” Notion’s page history is also plan-limited (7/30/90 days unless Enterprise). 
 And big exports can fail or fall back to HTML. 

Here’s the setup that won’t drift into copy-chaos again.

GitHub is the master, GitHub Pages is the public bookshelf, PDFs are downloadable artifacts

Curriculum “source” lives in a private repo (Markdown + assets)

One canonical branch (main).

Changes only via pull requests (review/approval = your CEO-proof receipt trail).

GitHub Pages hosts the live curriculum site (always current)
Reality check: GitHub Pages is not truly “unlimited.” The published site is capped at 1 GB and there are soft limits (bandwidth/builds). 
 So we plan for that.

PDFs are generated automatically and made easy to download
Two ways, and you can use both:

A) Small/medium PDFs: host on the Pages site

Works fine as long as your total site stays under the Pages size limit. 

B) “Official” PDFs: attach to GitHub Releases (best practice)

GitHub explicitly recommends Releases for distributing large binaries. 

Your site links to the latest Release PDF(s) (“Download the official PDF here”).

This is the clean solution to “staff want PDFs,” while keeping the repo/site from bloating. GitHub also blocks single files over 100 MiB in the repo, so Releases prevent you from fighting that ceiling. 

Why Notion will keep biting you for this use case

Exports: Notion can export pages/databases to PDF, but large exports may come via email, and if PDF export fails it can export as HTML instead. 

Version history is plan-limited unless Enterprise, which is a problem if you need long-term audit trails for curriculum decisions. 

File handling has constraints; for example, Notion notes size limits and different behavior by plan. 

What I’d do in your situation

Build and govern in GitHub (master).

Publish on GitHub Pages (easy reading).

Generate PDFs every time you tag a version (v2022-baseline, v2026-combined-v1, etc.) and publish those PDFs as Release downloads.

If leadership insists on SharePoint later, you drop the PDF there as a “published copy” only. No editing.

If you want, I can lay out the exact folder structure and the build workflow (MkDocs + PDF generation + Pages deploy + Release PDF upload) so you can just paste it into a repo and be done.

