That plan is solid. It’s basically “controlled demolition + rebuild,” which is exactly how you stop curriculum drift.

Here’s the workflow I recommend so it stays clean, consistent, and GitHub-ready, while still letting you move step-by-step.

The build workflow (one step at a time, no chaos)

Source intake (what you upload)
For each document you upload, I will extract only:

Content that is still valid

Content that belongs in one of your buckets

Any policy/requirements that must remain verbatim (if applicable)

Everything else gets flagged as:

Outdated

Duplicative

Conflicting

Needs rewrite

Rewrite into “Curriculum Units” (GitHub format)
For each bucket, we will produce:

One Markdown page per unit (or per subunit if it’s long)

A standard structure so every page looks and reads the same:

Purpose

Learning outcomes

Key terms

Core content

Instructor notes (optional, can be a separate staff-only build later)

Deliverables / artifacts (what students submit)

Time estimate / pacing (if you want it)

Truth control (the “no outdated info” rule)
Every time we rewrite:

If it’s stated in the doc: we keep it, cite it, or rewrite it cleanly.

If it’s not in the doc: we don’t invent it.

If two docs conflict: we flag the conflict and pick the “new official” version intentionally (you decide, or you tell me the rule like “use the newest revision date”).

GitHub transfer ready outputs
Each unit will come with:

The Markdown file content

The intended filename and folder path (example: docs/01-intro/overview.md)

A short “Change Notes” block for your records (what was removed/updated and why)

How we prevent “glitches” and losing the thread

We keep a running “Curriculum Build Index” in this chat: a simple list of pages we’ve created and what source doc they came from.

We never try to rewrite the whole universe in one shot. One bucket/unit per pass.

What I need from you (one decision, then you can just upload)
Pick the first build target:
A) Start with the “shell” pages (program overview, structure, dimensions, glossary, navigation), or
B) Start with a high-impact teaching unit (like Professional Development Principles or Shop Introduction)

