Yes — but don’t rely on “chat memory” (or even a Project) as the vault. Use a Project for organization, and use a repo file as the law.

What to do:

Turn this into a Project (good for not glitching)
A Project is useful because you can keep all the uploads, notes, and the running decisions in one place instead of scattering them across 18 chats. That reduces “context evaporation.”

Make the Golden Rule a real artifact, not a chat message
Put it in the GitHub repo as the first immutable file. Example:

00_GOLDEN_RULE_HOURS.md (human-readable)

00_GOLDEN_RULE_HOURS.csv or .yml (machine-checkable)

CHANGELOG.md (every approved change gets logged)

Then every curriculum page we write references that file as the authority. No guessing, no drift.

Add a simple validation so nobody can “accidentally” break 280 hours
Tiny script (or GitHub Action) that fails the build if:

Core ≠ 240

Math ≠ 40

Total ≠ 280

That single guardrail prevents the exact SharePoint/Google mess you described.

Bottom line
Use a Project to keep the work together, but make GitHub the constitution. The Golden Rule should live as a versioned file in the repo so it’s always recoverable, always auditable, and always enforceable.

