1) docs/professional-development/grit-growth-mindset/index.md  (Student-facing)
--- START FILE ---
---
title: Grit & Growth Mindset
audience: Student
time_required: 60 minutes
module_type: Professional Development
---

# Grit & Growth Mindset (60 minutes)

## Why this matters on a job site
In the trades, you will learn new skills under real pressure: time limits, feedback from others, and mistakes that cost time and money. This module gives you a simple mental framework to stay coachable and consistent when learning gets hard.

## What you will learn today
By the end of this module, you should be able to:
- Define grit and explain why it matters in the trades.
- Explain the difference between a fixed mindset and a growth mindset.
- Use a simple set of strategies to practice grit and a growth mindset.
- Set one short, realistic goal and commit to one action this week.

## Key definitions
### Grit
Grit = perseverance and passion for long-term goals.  
Plain language: sticking with something that matters, even when it gets hard.

### Mindset
A mindset is the way you think about your ability to learn and improve.

### Fixed mindset vs growth mindset
- Fixed mindset: “I’m either good at it or I’m not.” Mistakes feel like proof you can’t.
- Growth mindset: “I can get better.” Mistakes are part of learning.

## Five ways to build a growth mindset using grit
Use these like mental tools:
1. Embrace challenges.
2. Persist in the face of setbacks.
3. Value effort.
4. Learn from feedback.
5. Find lessons and inspiration in the success of others.

## Quick reflection (construction lens)
Answer in complete thoughts:
1. When you’re learning a new skill, what usually makes you shut down or get frustrated?
2. What does “taking feedback” look like on a job site (tone, speed, ego, communication)?
3. What is one way you can respond to mistakes that helps you learn instead of spiraling?

## Being Gritty: worksheet (in-class)
Write your answers clearly. Be specific.

1) A goal I’m excited about (something I actually care about):
- Goal:

2) Leaning into difficulty:
- The most common obstacle I face when working toward this goal:

3) This week’s action:
- One thing I will do this week to move toward my goal:

4) Mental habit:
- A mental habit I need to build (or break) to reach my goal:

## Commit to Grit (closing)
Answer these before you leave:
1) How will you remind yourself to stay gritty and practice a growth mindset?
2) Who will you ask to remind you?
3) What is one thing you will do this week to show grit?
4) When will you do it?

Name:
Date:
--- END FILE ---


2) docs/professional-development/grit-growth-mindset/instructor.md  (Instructor-facing)
--- START FILE ---
---
title: Grit & Growth Mindset — Instructor Guide
audience: Instructor
time_required: 60 minutes
module_type: Professional Development
---

# Grit & Growth Mindset — Instructor Guide (60 minutes)

## Scope
This guide is the compliant 60-minute version. Do not try to force extra videos, extra assignments, or extended discussion. If you want extensions, create a separate “Optional Extension” page later.

## Objectives (students must leave with)
Students will:
- Define grit.
- Identify fixed vs growth mindset thinking.
- Practice a short reflection and set one realistic goal.
- Commit to one action they will do this week.

## Materials
- Whiteboard / chart paper (definitions + examples)
- Student worksheet section (embedded in the student page)

## 60-minute run-of-show (minute-by-minute)

### 0:00–0:05 (5 min) — Set the frame
Say: “In the trades, you learn under pressure. This is about staying coachable and consistent when learning gets hard.”
Write on board:
- Grit
- Fixed mindset
- Growth mindset

### 0:05–0:15 (10 min) — Definitions + job site translation
Teach in plain language:
- Grit = sticking with long-term goals even when it’s hard.
- Fixed mindset = “I’m either good at it or not.”
- Growth mindset = “I can improve with practice and feedback.”
Ask:
- “Where do you see this in construction training or on a crew?”
Keep it concrete, no therapy session.

### 0:15–0:25 (10 min) — Spot it: fixed vs growth
Make two columns on the board:
Fixed mindset statements → Growth mindset rewrites
Examples:
- “I’m just not good at this.” → “I’m not good at this yet. Show me the standard.”
- “I always mess up.” → “I’m learning. I need reps and feedback.”
Have 2–3 students rewrite one statement out loud.

### 0:25–0:40 (15 min) — Teach the tool: 5 ways
Students write the “5 ways” down:
1) Embrace challenges
2) Persist through setbacks
3) Value effort
4) Learn from feedback
5) Learn from others’ success
For each “way,” ask for one construction example:
- learning a tool
- taking correction
- repeating a task until it’s right
- staying safe when tired
- showing up on time consistently

### 0:40–0:55 (15 min) — Student worksheet: Being Gritty
Students complete the four prompts:
- goal
- obstacle
- one action this week
- mental habit to build/break
Instructor moves:
- Push students toward specific actions (“10 minutes/day practice” beats “try harder”).
- If someone is stuck, give a trade example and have them mirror the structure.

### 0:55–1:00 (5 min) — Commit to Grit (closing)
Students answer the 4 closing questions.
Close line: “Motivation comes and goes. Systems and habits keep you moving.”

## Fast checks for understanding (30 seconds each)
Ask 3 students:
1) Define grit in their own words.
2) Give one fixed mindset thought.
3) Rewrite it as growth mindset.
4) State their one action for the week.

## Notes / restrictions
- Do NOT use restricted videos (e.g., Sista). This module is designed to run without video.
--- END FILE ---


