ChatGPT said:

Thought for 45s
That warning is telling you one very specific thing: Playwright is trying to download Chromium/Chrome from Google Cloud Storage, and in the Copilot coding-agent environment outbound downloads to that host are blocked by firewall rules. So the agent can’t install the browser binaries it needs.

You fix it by choosing one of these paths (pick based on whether you actually need Playwright).

Best fix if you don’t need Playwright right now: stop requiring it
If your repo is just building a curriculum site (Markdown → Pages) and Playwright isn’t essential, remove or skip the step that triggers it.

Common places to check:

requirements.txt / pyproject.toml includes playwright

GitHub Actions workflow runs tests or a script that imports Playwright

A “PDF generation” step uses Playwright/Puppeteer under the hood

Quick workaround: set Playwright to not download browsers during CI (only if you are not running browser-based tests in CI):

export PLAYWRIGHT_SKIP_BROWSER_DOWNLOAD=1
If you are running Playwright tests, this won’t work (tests will fail because no browser exists).

If you do need Playwright: install browsers before the firewall kicks in (Copilot agent setup steps)
That warning literally tells you the fix: run the install in the repo’s Copilot coding agent setup steps (these run before the firewall is enabled), or allowlist the host.

Add a setup step that does one of these (Python repo):

python -m pip install -r requirements.txt
python -m playwright install chromium
Or for Node:

npm ci
npx playwright install chromium
This makes the browser download happen during the “allowed” phase.

Admin-only alternative: allowlist the blocked host
If you have admin rights and you want the agent to be able to download normally, allowlist:

storage.googleapis.com

or specifically chrome-for-testing-public (as shown in the URLs)

This is done in the repository’s Copilot coding agent settings (wherever your org exposes “custom allowlist”).

Most reliable CI approach: use a Playwright container image (no browser download)
If this is happening in your CI and you want it rock-solid, run the job in a Microsoft Playwright container that already includes browsers. You choose a tag that matches your Playwright version.

Example pattern (you’ll need to adjust to your workflow file and version):

jobs:
  test:
    runs-on: ubuntu-latest
    container: mcr.microsoft.com/playwright/python:YOUR_TAG_HERE
    steps:
      - uses: actions/checkout@v4
      - run: python -m pip install -r requirements.txt
      - run: pytest
One important detail from your paste: it also says “All checks have passed” and one check was skipped. That means this warning is likely from the Copilot agent trying to do something extra, not necessarily blocking your merge.

Fastest way to tell you exactly which option fits: tell me what in your repo is using Playwright (tests? PDF generation? something else) and whether this warning is coming from Copilot’s PR run or your normal GitHub Actions workflow.

