Thought for 50s
That warning isn’t about your MkDocs content. It’s Copilot’s coding agent trying to run Playwright, which then tries to download a Chrome binary from storage.googleapis.com, and the agent’s firewall blocks it.

Good news: your PR can still be merged. “All checks have passed” means this warning is not stopping deploy. If you want it gone (and keep the agent happy), pick one of these fixes.

Option 1 (simplest): stop triggering Playwright at all
If this repo is just a MkDocs curriculum site, you don’t need Playwright.

Do this:

Search your repo for what’s calling Playwright:

In GitHub: search for playwright install

Also search: pytest-playwright, playwright, npx playwright, python -m playwright

Remove that step from workflows/scripts, OR gate it so it doesn’t run in this repo.

If you still need the Python package but do NOT need browsers in CI, add an environment variable to the job that installs deps:

PLAYWRIGHT_SKIP_BROWSER_DOWNLOAD=1
(Only use this if you are not running browser tests/screenshot automation.)

Option 2 (agent-focused): preinstall before the firewall
This warning is specifically about the Copilot coding agent environment. If you want Copilot to keep generating screenshots/previews that rely on Playwright, you must either:

A) Add “setup steps” for the Copilot coding agent that run before the firewall, and install browsers there:

python -m pip install -r requirements.txt
python -m playwright install chromium
B) Admin-only: allowlist the host in Copilot coding agent settings
Allowlist:

storage.googleapis.com
(or whatever host your Playwright downloads hit)

Option 3 (most reliable): don’t download browsers at all
If you actually do need browser automation in CI, use a Playwright container image (browsers already included) and stop downloading during runs. This is more work, but it eliminates the whole class of failures.

What I would do in your situation
Because your PR is just adding MkDocs pages + CSS + nav: use Option 1. Remove/gate whatever is invoking Playwright so the repo stays “boring” and dependable.

