ChatGPT said:

Thought for 11s
You’ve got two separate blockers:

The PR is a Draft → drafts can’t be merged.

The branch is out of date → merge conflicts across a bunch of files.

Fix order: resolve conflicts first (so the PR is clean), then mark it “Ready for review.”

Resolve the conflicts (command line)
This is the standard, boring, reliable way:

Update your local repo and switch to the PR branch

git fetch origin
git checkout <your-branch-name>
git pull
Merge the base branch into your branch (usually main)

git merge origin/main
Git will stop and tell you which files conflicted. For each conflicted file:

Open it

Find the conflict markers:

<<<<<<<

=======

>>>>>>>

Decide what the final content should be

Delete the markers

Save

Mark conflicts as resolved and commit

git add .github/workflows/pages.yml .gitignore CHANGELOG.md README.md \
  curriculum_data/golden_rule_hours.yaml docs/governance/golden-rule.md \
  docs/governance/single-source.md docs/index.md docs/stylesheets/extra.css \
  docs/stylesheets/pdf.css mkdocs.yml requirements.txt scripts/validate_golden_rule.py

git commit -m "Resolve merge conflicts with main"
Push back up to GitHub

git push
After that, refresh the PR page. The “conflicts must be resolved” message should be gone.

If you prefer rebase instead of merge (cleaner history, slightly more annoying)

git fetch origin
git checkout <your-branch-name>
git rebase origin/main
# resolve conflicts as they appear
git add <file>
git rebase --continue
git push --force-with-lease
Important: only use rebase if you’re comfortable with --force-with-lease.

Then fix the Draft status
On the PR page:

Click “Ready for review” (or “Mark as ready”).
That removes the “Draft pull requests cannot be merged” blocker.

